      <p>The SIHIO M18 is the Branch's closest competitor. It costs $66 less, includes a headrest, and has a similar mesh back. Where it loses is lumbar adjustability (height only), warranty (3 years versus 7), armrests (3D versus 4D), and seat foam density. If the $66 matters to you or you specifically want the headrest included, the SIHIO is the pick. Otherwise the Branch is the better long-term buy.</p>

      <p>The Hbada is the budget pick and the right choice for sitting under 4 hours a day. At $130 it is less than half the Branch's price, and for part-time use it is genuinely good value. For full-time work, the Branch's 7-year warranty makes it cheaper per year of use — five Hbadas at $130 each last the same 7 years as one Branch at $345.</p>

      <p>The Herman Miller Aeron is the premium benchmark and the chair every ergonomic chair is compared against. It is meaningfully better on every metric — better mesh, better lumbar, better seat (tensioned mesh, not foam), better build, and a 12-year warranty. But it costs $1,395, which is four times the Branch's price. For most home office workers, the Branch delivers 80 percent of the Aeron experience for a quarter of the cost. Read our <a href="/reviews/herman-miller-aeron-review/">Herman Miller Aeron review</a> to decide if the premium is worth it for you.</p>

      <p>The Steelcase Leap V2 is the other premium benchmark worth knowing about. It uses upholstery rather than mesh, which makes it warmer and softer than the Aeron. It is the chair we recommend for buyers who find mesh backs too firm or too cold. Like the Aeron, it starts around $1,000 and climbs with options. Our <a href="/reviews/steelcase-leap-v2-review/">Steelcase Leap V2 review</a> covers when it is worth the upgrade.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Branch Ergonomic Chair if you sit 6 or more hours per day and your budget is in the $300 to $500 range. It is the best chair in that tier, and the 7-year warranty means it will outlast two or three budget chairs. If you sit fewer than 4 hours a day, save the money and buy the $130 Hbada — the Branch's advantages only pay off over long sessions.</p>

      <p>Choose the SIHIO M18 instead if you specifically want a headrest included or the $66 savings matters to you. The SIHIO is the runner-up on merit, not on price — it is a genuinely good chair that loses to the Branch on adjustability and warranty rather than on comfort. If you recline while reading or taking calls, the included headrest makes the SIHIO the better choice for your workflow.</p>

      <p>Add the headrest to the Branch if you recline. The $49 add-on is height-adjustable and attaches with two bolts. If you only sit upright to type, skip it — the headrest is useless in an upright posture and just adds visual clutter.</p>

      <p>Replace the castors if your office is carpeted. The included nylon castors on all three chairs are fine on hard floors but struggle on medium-pile carpet. A set of rollerblade-style polyurethane castors costs about $30 on Amazon and makes any of these chairs roll noticeably easier. If your office is hard floor, the stock castors are fine.</p>

      <p>Complete your ergonomic setup. A good chair solves posture, but your desk and monitor still need attention. Pair the chair with a standing desk or a standing desk converter if you want to add sit-stand without replacing your desk. Add a monitor riser to bring your screen to eye level, and add a foot rest to take pressure off your thighs during long sessions. The combination of a good chair, a desk at the right height, and a monitor at eye level is what actually prevents the neck and back pain that drives people to buy ergonomic chairs in the first place.</p>

      <p>If $345 is genuinely out of reach, do not stretch. The <a href="/reviews/best-ergonomic-chair-budget/">budget ergonomic chair roundup</a> covers chairs from $130 up, and the Hbada handles 4-hour days fine. Save the upgrade budget for a standing desk converter or a monitor riser — those two upgrades change how your body feels more than swapping a $130 chair for a $345 one.</p>

